partOf.title:
Exploration and exploitation in the
macrohistory of the pre-Hispanic Pueblo Southwest

p0m9pcg.editorialNote:
These are revised Pecos period definitions (including subperiods) derived explicitly from a large
database of tree-ring cutting dates from across the Ancestral Pueblo Southwest. Basketmaker III is truncated to start at
AD 500; Pueblo IV is truncated to end at AD 1400; all periods are rounded to the nearest 5th year. We wanted to identify
the points in time when the rate of change in the cutting-date frequency was transitioning from slowing down to
accelerating, to break up Fig. 2B into five Pecos periods (and their subperiods) based on the four primary
“humps” in the cutting-date frequency distribution. To do so, we calculated the modal inflection points (the
points at which a continuous vector switches from being concave to being convex, or vice versa) in a series of kernel
density estimates of the number of cells with cutting dates through time (Fig. 2B), each using a Gaussian kernel (that
is, a normal distribution). Because the smoothness of kernel density distributions is determined by the kernel bandwidth
(here, the SD of the Gaussian kernel), we estimated inflection points for density distributions with kernel bandwidths
ranging from 0.01 to 50 years, in 0.01-year increments (5000 kernel density estimates). For each density distribution,
we calculated a series of inflection points as the years where the second derivative of the kernel density estimate
function was zero. Kernel distributions with very small bandwidths will have many inflection points, whereas those with
large bandwidths (that is, very smooth distributions) will only have a few. The inflection points of each of the kernel
density distributions were combined to calculate the 10 most common inflection years. Inflection years were rounded to
the nearest fifth year. One break in the P IV period (at A.D. 1365) was discarded because P IV was determined to not fit
the demographic and organizational pattern of the earlier periods. All source code for defining these periods are
available at http://advances.sciencemag.org/cgi/ content/full/2/4/e1501532/DC1.

NOTES:

This
table of major Chinese States and Dynasties provides a basic time frame, and includes both the overall periods, as well
as specific sub-periods, or in most cases, specific states.

For example, the Northern and Southern Dynasties is
listed (420 CE - 577 CE), along with the various states, such as Liu Song, Eastern Wei, and so on that existed during
that period.    Note that the overall period is not itself a "state" and has no capital, nor any administration or
political history.  It is merely a superset of many states.

By contrast there are Periods, with Sub-periods, such as
the Song Dynasty, which was one continuous political entity, but is divided into two very distinct periods, the Northern
Song and Southern Song, reflecting the incursion of the Mongols who seized the greater part of the northern area of the
Song, and forced the capital to be relocated from Kaifeng to Hangzhou.

p0trc5r.editorialNote:
These are the primary Pecos periods
(Basketmaker II – Pueblo III) as derived from the 1999 Colorado "context document." Being part of the Colorado
contexts, these periods are specific to southwestern Colorado; however, they have been generally applied across the Four
Corners region and broader San Juan basin. Period definitions are given at the title of each chapter of the Contexts;
the "locator within source" points to the table of contents.

p0tns5v4kdf.note:
This period is used to designate the moment of
Phoenician colonization in the West before the development of a distinctive Punic identity.

p0tns5v56hf.editorialNote:
Hodos notes that the end of the Iron Age "segues into the Archaic phase of Classical civilization,
which coincides with the Punic era of Mediterranean history, the full development of the city-state in the Greek world,
and the very beginning of Rome's Republican period" (4); also notes that "in the Near East, Iron Age terminology is
replaced in the sixth century BC with Persian periodization" -- so inference is that the Iron Age ceases to apply at
some point around the 6th c. BC.

p0gjgrsg24g.note:
This period does not appear in the EH timeline. When this broad period is used, the database will automatically
map it onto either Iron Age (for the earlier coins) or Roman (for the later coins) depending on the precise years
entered.

p0gjgrshhcw.label: Early Medieval
p0gjgrshhcw.note:
This period is diverse and must be qualified wherever possible with
Early, Middle or Late. The currently accepted chronology (spring 2013) is given below, but this is likely to change in
the near future. English Heritage do not specify the boundaries of these sub-periods.

p0gjgrs45g4.label: Mesolithic
p0gjgrs45g4.note: Can be split into Early and Late.

p0gjgrs6sgx.label: Post-Medieval
p0gjgrs6sgx.note:
Early post-medieval is generally used for the 16th
century and sometimes for the 17th century. The term 'middle post-medieval' is not used, and there is debate as to what
constitutes the late post-medieval period. For the 18th century, it is best to stick simply to 'post-medieval' and
qualify it using calendar dates.

Greek and
Roman Provincial

later coins) depending on the precise years entered.

ou pied en bourrelet; décor en noir mat (rares retouches rouges)"

p05n4hjrw5p.label: Age néolithique
p05n4hjrw5p.editorialNote:
Neolithic
period collection restricted to Plates 1 and 2
p05n4hjrw5p.note:
Les fouilles de Troie conduites par Schliemann de 1870 à 1890,
continuées par Doerpfeld en 1893-94, ont donné lieu à nombreuses publications dont on trouvera les
références dans Perrot et Chipiez, 'Hist. de l'art', VI, p. 154 et suiv., p. 895 et suiv.; Dussaud, 'Les
Civilisations préhelléniques, 2e édit., p. 118 et suiv. Parmi les principales nous citerons: Schliemann,
'Ilios', 1881; trad. française Egger, 1885; C. Schuchhardt, 'Schliemann's Ausgrahungen', 1891; Doerpfeld, 'Troja
und Ilion', 2 vol. 1902; H. Schmidt, 'Trojanisch. Alterthümer', 1902.

Pour le classement des poteries de ce
genre, voir, dans la série faite pour l'Union Académique Interntionale, la Classification (n. 7) de D.G.
Hogarth, 'Pottery of Asia Minor (except greek colonies)'.

source.title:
Peintures antiques et
inédites de vases grecs, tirées de diverses collections, avec des explications

p044mt9m8zd.label:
La
troisième époque

start.label: au temps de la seconde guerre Punique

p044mt9m8zd.editorialNote:
ISO values for Earliest and Latest Starts and Stops inferred from standard
modern chronologies for Second Punic and Social Wars (cf. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Punic_War#cite_ref-1 and
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_War_(91%E2%80%9388_BC). "La seconde guerre Punique" is inferred from the
reference to "cette guerre" at viii n. 9.

Though the source determines the chronological parameters of this period
based on political fluctuations that took place primarily if not exclusively in the Italian peninsula and Magna Graecia,
his introduction (cf. pp. i-vii) foregrounds his discussion of Greek vase painting as encompassing works made both in
Italy and in Greece (see, e.g.,  his discussion of Corinthian pottery on pp. vii and ix). I therefore included Greece in
the spatial coverage of this Period.
p044mt9m8zd.note:
La troisième époque commenceroit au temps de cette guerre désastrueuse et se
prolongeroit jusqu'à la guerre Sociale qui ruina de fond en comble l'Italie, et y détruisit entièrement
la civilisation et toutes les institutions que les Grecs y avoient apportées. [cf. Millingen 1813, viii n. 9]  Ce
fut probablement alors que cessa la fabrication des vases peints."

[Millingen 1813, viii n. 9]: "Du temps
d'Auguste, toute la Grande-Grèce étoit tombée dans la barbarie, à l'exception de Naples, de Rhegium,
et de Tarente, Strabo, lib. VI pag. a53. Edit. 1620"

p044mt93nd6.label: La seconde époque
p044mt93nd6.editorialNote:
"The Fine Style" alternate label from Birch
1858, 222 (citing Millingen 1813, viii).

Earliest and Latest Stop ISO values inferred from modern chronology of
Second Punic War (cf. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Punic_War#cite_ref-1).
p044mt93nd6.note:
"La seconde [époque] commençnt à
l'année 450, temps où ont fleuri Polygnote [cf. n. 7] et Phidias, est celle où l'Art a atteint son plus
haut dégré de perfection [cf. n. 8] elle finiroit quant à l'Italie et à la Sicile, vers la seconde
guerre Punique."

[Millingen 1813, viii n. 7]: "'Polygnote, qui florissoit dans la LXXXIIIème Olympiade (444.
ans avant notre ére) fut le premier qui peignit des femmes avec des vêtemens transparens, des coëffures
de différentes couleurs et qui contribua le premier à la perfection de l'Art, car il établit l'usage
d'ouvrir la bouche aux figures, de faire voir les dents, de changer l'ancienne roideur des attitudes, Plin. Hist. Nat.
lib. XXXV. cap. 9.'"

[Millingen 1813, viii, n. 8]: "L'Art paroit n'être parvenu à sa perfection que du
temps de Polygnote et de Phidias. Il est probable que sa marche n'à pas été tout à fait graduelle,
mais qu'il prit un essor sous ces grands artistes, comme celui que Raphaël fit prendre à l'art moderne."

p044mt9z8hr.label: La première époque
p044mt9z8hr.note:
"On sait
l'extrème difficulté qu'il y a de fixer l'époque des monumens anciens avec quelque dégré de
précision, soit en les considérant d'après le style de l'Art, soit d'après les principes de la
paléographie, lorsqu'ils présentent des caractères. Mais en combinant ce qu'ont rapporté les auteurs
anciens avec les monumens de toute espèce, surtout les médailles et les inscriptions, il semble qu'on peut
établir trois époques principales." (Millingen 1813, viii)

cf. Millingen 1813, n. 6: "V. Planches XX
à XXII, XXXI, XXXII".

source.title:
Iron Age Archaeology of
the Northwest Iberian Peninsula

p0hvcwrjpsf.label: Early Iron Age
p0hvcwrjpsf.note:
Contemporary with Hallstatt B-D (S. Germany). Overlaps LBA III/
Tartessian period, 750-600 B.C. (- cf. M. Diaz-Andreu & S. Keay, 1997. The Archaeology of Iberia.); includes Iberian I
(600-500 B.C.) and II (500-450 B.C.) (ibid.). See also T. Chapa & M. Belen, 1997. La Edad del Hierro.

p02q72z37m3.label: Zweiten Periode
p02q72z37m3.editorialNote:
Gerhard's dating is based on letter forms matched to the historical record and placed chronologically
by Olympiad. See also citation of this source in Birch 1858 (p. 221).
p02q72z37m3.note:
Period label: "Einer zweiten Periode, welche in
jenen, hauptsächlich den Gefäfsen etruskischer Auffindung angehörigen Zeitraum." Spatial coverage:
"...fallen denn, ebenfalls aus paläographischen und zugleich aus artistischen Gründen, die meisten Vasen
Siciliens und Kampaniens, hauptsächlich Nola's anheim". Gerhard identifies a third period that follows this one;
it is characterized by works from Apulia and Lucania, but is not given any absolute dates: "dagegen eine dritte
spätere Periode jener Vasenfabrikation den apulischen und lukanischen Vasen beizumessen ist." (1836, 144).

p02q72z6c67.label: Vorgerückten Kunstsitte
p02q72z6c67.editorialNote:
See also Birch (1858, p. 221), who cites this page in Gerhard, though note that he attributes the starting point to
Olymp. LXXXIV (444 BCE) in an apparent misreading of Gerhard's text.
p02q72z6c67.note:
Period label: "Vasen mit denen einer
vorgerückten Kunstsitte". Spatial coverage: "von Volci aus alle umliegenden Gegenden Etruriens mit
Thongefäfsen griechischer Kunst". Dates based principally on the appearance of distinct Greek letter forms on some
of the vases within the museum collection. From Gerhard 1836, 144: "Fast alle dort gefundenen Vaseninschriften zeigen
uns einen allgemeinen Gebrauch des simonideischen Alphabets, während sie mit wenigen Ausnahmen die euklideischen
Doppelvokale verleugnen, wonach denn für die Mehrzahl jener Gefäfse der Zeitabschnitt von Olymp. LXXIV bis
Olymp. XCIV begrenzend eintritt."

source.title: Heritage Data | Linked Data Vocabularies for Cultural Heritage

p0kh9ds9nsj.label: Roman
p0kh9ds9nsj.note:
Traditionally begins with the Roman invasion in 43AD and
ends with the emperor Honorius directing Britain to see to its own defence in 410AD.

p0kh9ds3566.label:
First
World War
p0kh9ds3566.note:
Used to record buildings, defensive monuments and sites dating to, and associated with, the First World War.
For other types of building, such as houses, built during this period use EARLY 20TH CENTURY.

p0kh9dsqx6c.label: Middle Iron Age
p0kh9dsqx6c.note: The second subdivision of the Iron Age.

p0kh9dszj78.label: 21st Century
p0kh9dszj78.note: Twenty first century phases and events.

p0kh9dscbkd.label: Medieval
p0kh9dscbkd.note:
The Medieval period or Middle Ages begins with the Norman invasion and ends with the dissolution of the
monasteries.

p0kh9dsw3zv.label: Edwardian
p0kh9dsw3zv.note:
The period covering the reign of Edward VII. Do not use
for the reigns of Edwards I-VI.

p0kh9dsbm2h.label: Middle Neolithic
p0kh9dsbm2h.note:
The second subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone
Age.

p0kh9dsdf5j.label: Early Prehistoric
p0kh9dsdf5j.note:
For monuments which are characteristic of the
Paleolithic to Mesolithic but cannot be specifically assigned.

p0kh9dst3vc.label: Georgian
p0kh9dst3vc.note:
Dating to or characteristic of the reigns of any of the
first four kings of Great Britain called George

p0kh9dsbd33.label: Cold War
p0kh9dsbd33.note:
The period of political and military opposition betwen
the major Superpowers (USA and USSR) and their allies. Known as the Cold War as there were no direct military conflicts
between the two main protagonists.

p0kh9ds6t9k.label: Early Mesolithic
p0kh9ds6t9k.note:
The earliest subdivision of the Mesolithic, or Middle
Stone Age.

p0kh9dstffb.label: Early 20th Century
p0kh9dstffb.note: The first third of the 20th century.

p0kh9dscmjf.label: Late Mesolithic
p0kh9dscmjf.note: The latest subdivision of the Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age.

p0kh9dszskn.label: Early Iron Age
p0kh9dszskn.note: The earliest subdivision of the Iron Age.

p0kh9dstr3n.label: Elizabethan
p0kh9dstr3n.note: Dating to the reign of Elizabeth 1st of England.

p0kh9dsqpzm.label: Middle Bronze Age
p0kh9dsqpzm.note: The second subdivision of the Bronze Age.

p0kh9dsxp46.label: Victorian
p0kh9dsxp46.note: Dating to the reign of Queen Victoria

p0kh9ds3whd.label: Jacobean
p0kh9ds3whd.note: Dating to the reign of James I of England (VI of Scotland)

p0kh9ds5x8v.label: Second World War
p0kh9ds5x8v.note:
Used to record buildings, defensive monuments and sites
dating to, and associated with, the Second World War. For other types of building, such as houses, built during this
period use MID 20TH CENTURY.

p0kh9ds785r.label: Later Prehistoric
p0kh9ds785r.note:
For monuments that can be identifed only to a date
range from Neolithic to Iron Age.

p0kh9dstmtg.label: Lower Palaeolithic
p0kh9dstmtg.note:
The earliest subdivision of the Palaeolithic, or
Old Stone Age; when the earliest use of flint tools appears in the current archaeological record. A hunter gatherer
society is a defining characteristic.

p0kh9ds8p8k.label: Late Iron Age
p0kh9ds8p8k.note: The third and latest subdivision of the Iron Age.

p0kh9ds6f4n.label: Stuart
p0kh9ds6f4n.note: Dating to the reign of the Stuart kings of England (including the Commonwealth inter-regnum)

p0kh9dst7t7.label: Prehistoric
p0kh9dst7t7.note: For monuments that can be identifed only to a date range from Palaeolithic to Iron Age.

p0kh9dshs59.label: Early Bronze Age
p0kh9dshs59.note: The earliest subdivision of the Bronze Age.

p0kh9dsqfgv.label: Palaeolithic
p0kh9dsqfgv.note:
The Old Stone Age defined by the practice of
hunting and gathering and the use of chipped flint tools. This period is usually divided up into the Lower, Middle and
Upper Palaeolithic.

p0kh9dsk4zt.label: Mid 20th Century
p0kh9dsk4zt.note: The mid third of the 20th Century

p0kh9dsbnzg.label: Early Neolithic
p0kh9dsbnzg.note: The earliest subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.

p0kh9dsbz2g.label: Neolithic
p0kh9dsbz2g.note:
The New Stone Age, this period follows on from the Palaeolithic and the Mesolithc and is itself
suceeded by the Bronze Age. This period is characterized by the practice of a farming ecomony and extensive monumental
constructions.

p0kh9dsvcdn.label: Hanoverian
p0kh9dsvcdn.note: Dating to the reign of the Hanoverian kings.

p0kh9dsj33x.label: Iron Age
p0kh9dsj33x.note:
This period follows on from the Bronze Age and is characterized by the use of iron for making
tools and monuments such as hillforts and oppida. The Iron Age is taken to end with the Roman invasion.

p0kh9dsqkbq.label: Late Bronze Age
p0kh9dsqkbq.note: The third and latest subdivision of the Bronze Age.

p0kh9dsmf3f.label: Early Medieval
p0kh9dsmf3f.note:
This dates from the breakdown of Roman rule in Britain to the Norman invasion in 1066 and is to be used for
monuments of post Roman, Saxon and Viking date.

p0kh9ds4hjq.label: Late Neolithic
p0kh9ds4hjq.note:
The third and latest subdivision of the Neolithic, or
New Stone Age.

p0kh9dsctsj.label: Post Medieval
p0kh9dsctsj.note:
Begins with the dissolution of the monasteries and ends
with the death of Queen Victoria. Use more specific period where known.

p0kh9ds7jvs.label: Tudor
p0kh9ds7jvs.note: Dating to the reign of the Tudor monarchs

p0kh9ds7q8m.label: Bronze Age
p0kh9ds7q8m.note:
This period follows on from the Neolithic and is characterized by the increasing use of
Bronzework. It is subdivided in the Early,Middle and Late Bronze Age.

p0kh9dsnrhc.label: Middle Palaeolithic
p0kh9dsnrhc.note:
The second subdivision of the Paleolithic or Old

p0kh9dsts5m.note:

development of projectile points made from bony materials and the development of fine blade flint tools.

p0kh9dskb4m.label: Mesolithic
p0kh9dskb4m.note:
The Middle Stone Age, falling between the Palaeolithic and the Neolithic; marks the beginning of
a move from a hunter gatherer society towards food producing society.

source.abstract:
The document
shows the chrono-cultural categories that are employed to classify archaeological entities within the Sistema de
Información Arqueológica (Archaelogical Information System, SIA+) of Incipit CSIC.
Chrono-cultural categories
are not exactly periods. They have strong chronological semantics but also possess cultural meaning. This is an arguable
way to categorise archaeological entities, but nevertheless they have been used by Incipit CSIC on the SIA+ for over 18
years, and currently characterise over 200.000 entities from Galicia and neighbouring areas in NW Spain.
source.title:
SIA+ Chrono-Cultural
Categories

p0d39r7d5km.label: Iron Age

p0znh3t5s5w.label: Fine Style
p0znh3t5s5w.editorialNote:
Author apparently miscalculates Start date as "Ol. XCIV, B.C. 403". The 94th Olympiad would range
from 400 to 396 BC (ISO values: -399 to -395). I have opted to use his more precise dating of "B.C. 403" as a precise
Start.

It is unclear whether author indicates the lifespan or the reign of Pyrrhus when indicating "the time of
Pyrrhus" as the period in which the florid style gradually replaced the fine style. I have therefore opted for the
wider range (Pyrrhus' life) to infer an earliest and latest stop. cf.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyrrhus_of_Epirus#cite_note-1
p0znh3t5s5w.note:
p.285: "The age of these vases is fixed
by the appearance of the long vowels, the changed form of the aspirate, and the presence of the double or aspirated
letters, introduced into the public acts after the archonship of Euclid, Olympiad XCIV., B.C. 403."

p.288-90: "It
is by no means necessary to suppose that one style of fabric ceased immediately on the introduction of another and
improved one; on the contrary, it probably continued till so entirely superseded that the fabric became obsolete. Hence
the transition from the 'fine' style of the earlier vases to a subsequent one, which may be termed florid -- analogous
to the state of art in the time of Pyrrhus."

p0znh3tjqgh.label: Decadence
p0znh3tjqgh.note:
p.
296: "The vases of this style at its best period are later than the introduction of the double letters in the
Archonship of Euclid, Olympiad XCIV, B.C. 404, and come down to nearly B.C. 200. [see note 4]"

p.296, n. 4:
"Thiersch., s. 81-2"

p0znh3t4t68.label: Florid Style
p0znh3t4t68.editorialNote:
It
is unclear whether the author means the lifespan or reign of Pyrrhus in his description. I have therefore inferred a
Start and Stop date from Pyrrhus' lifespan (the broader range). cf.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyrrhus_of_Epirus#cite_note-1
p0znh3t4t68.note:
p. 288-290: "It is by no means
necessary to suppose that one style of fabric ceased immediately on the introduction of another and improved one; on the
contrary, it probably continued till so entirely superseded that the fabric became obsolete. Hence the transition from
the 'fine' style of the earlier vases to a subsequent one, which may be termed florid--analogous to the state of art in
the time of Pyrrhus."

p0znh3tjnv8.label: Strong Style
p0znh3tjnv8.note:
p. 282: "The age of these vases is
placed between the L. and LXXX. Olympiads. Recent discoveries have shown that vases of this style are as old as the
Parthenon, destroyed by the Persians, Ol. LXXV., B.C. 480, and certainly prior to the age of Pheidias. [see note 3] The
vases with the historical subjects of Alcaeus, Ol. XLII., B.C. 612; Anacreon, Ol. LV., B.C. 560; and Croesus, Ol.
LVIII., B.C. 548, are in this style. The alphabet resembles that which appears in the Athenian inscriptions of Ol.
LXXXVI., B.C. 436, but the language is both Attic and Doric."

p.282 n.3: "Jahn, Vasensammlung, s. clxxiv. clxxv;
Allg. Monatsschr, 1852, p. 356."

periods (3250-3000 B.C.), and Ur of the Chaldees (1150-800 B.C.). Note this quote p.15: "At an archaeological congress
of excavators held at Baghdad in 1929 it was agreed that the early stages of human settlement in south Mesopotamia could
be classified n successive phases which should be called, after the places where the evidence for each was first
discovered, the al-'Ubaid period, the Uruk period, the Jamdat Nasr period, and then the Early Dynastic period, towards
the end of which (in IIIb) comes the First Dynasty of Ur." p.16: "Archaeological excavation ... does not of itself

p0dfxxptx7v.label: Upper Paleolithic
p0dfxxptx7v.note:
Modified from Shea (2013*: 7,
table 1.1), whose focus is on the Levant. This rough chronology is primarily uncalibrated; calibration is only relevant
for more recent periods, and even for these, most dates, particularly from earlier research, are presented as
uncalibrated. *Stone Tools in the Paleolithic and Neolithic Near East. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge.

p0dfxxpcnkv.label: Aceramic Neolithic
p0dfxxpcnkv.note:
Modified from Shea (2013*: 7, table 1.1), whose focus is on the Levant. *Stone Tools in the
Paleolithic and Neolithic Near East. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge. These start & end dates are calibrated. A
large regional chronological variability is observed here, as with the Epipaleolithic. Typically, the Neolithic on the
islands is later than on the mainland, having derived from that region. However, an early Neolithic contemporary with
that of the mainland has been recently documented in Cyprus; thus, the wide chronological framework is used here, which
includes both Pre-Pottery and Pottery phases.

p0dfxxpp4m9.label: Epipaleolithic
p0dfxxpp4m9.note:
Modified from Shea (2013*: 7, table 1.1), whose focus
is on the Levant. *Stone Tools in the Paleolithic and Neolithic Near East. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge. This
end date is calibrated. The time range for the Epipaleolithic varies considerably, based on regions. For the mainland,
the range is generally that given in this table; this is also when calibrated dates typically are used. However, for
most Mediterranean islands, the Epipaleolithic often starts much later and continues into what is generally considered
Neolithic on the mainland.
